post_cb({"18742323": {"CommentCount": "3", "ViewCount": "735", "CreationDate": "2013-09-11T13:18:29.230", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-11T13:26:56.417", "PostTypeId": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "18742440", "FavoriteCount": "3", "Title": "Can nullptr be used as a variable argument (varargs)?", "Id": "18742323", "Score": "20", "Body": "<p>Can I use the <code>nullptr</code> keyword as an argument for a variable function? If so, does it undergo any kind of standard conversion, and what is the type of the resulting value?</p>\n<p>Concretely, is the following correct?</p>\n<pre><code>std::printf(\"%p\", nullptr);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Or does it have to be:</p>\n<pre><code>std::printf(\"%p\", static_cast&lt;void *&gt;(nullptr));\n</code></pre>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><type-conversion><nullptr>", "OwnerUserId": "596781", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "18742440": {"ParentId": "18742323", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-11T13:26:56.417", "CommentCount": "3", "CreationDate": "2013-09-11T13:23:20.850", "OwnerUserId": "1670129", "LastEditorUserId": "752976", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "18742440", "Score": "22", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18742323_18742440_0\"><strong>\u00a75.2.2p7</strong> When there is no parameter for a given argument, the argument is passed in such a way that the receiving function can obtain the value of the argument by invoking <code>va_arg</code> (18.10)... An argument that has (possibly cv-qualified) type <code>std::nullptr_t</code> is converted to type <code>void*</code> (4.10)...</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-11T13:26:56.417"}, "18742418": {"ParentId": "18742323", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The standard says that any argument of type <code>nullptr_t</code> will be converted to <code>void*</code> when matching <code>...</code>.  So the call is correct without the cast. </p>\n<p>EDIT:</p>\n<p>From the standard (\u00a75.2.2/7): </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18742323_18742418_0\">When there is no parameter for a given argument, the argument is\n  passed in such a way that the receiving function can obtain the\n  value of the argument by invoking <code>va_arg</code>.  The\n  lvalue-to-rvalue, array-to-pointer, and function-to-pointer\n  standard conversions are performed on the argument expression.\n  An argument that has (possibly cv-qualified) type\n  <code>std::nullptr_t</code> is converted to type <code>void*</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "649665", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "18742418", "Score": "11", "CreationDate": "2013-09-11T13:22:39.023", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-11T13:22:39.023"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_18742323_18742440_0": {"section_id": 5994, "quality": 0.8928571428571429, "length": 25}, "so_18742323_18742418_0": {"section_id": 5994, "quality": 0.9696969696969697, "length": 32}}, "n3337": {"so_18742323_18742440_0": {"section_id": 5762, "quality": 0.8928571428571429, "length": 25}, "so_18742323_18742418_0": {"section_id": 5762, "quality": 0.9696969696969697, "length": 32}}, "n4659": {"so_18742323_18742440_0": {"section_id": 7496, "quality": 0.7857142857142857, "length": 22}, "so_18742323_18742418_0": {"section_id": 7496, "quality": 0.8787878787878788, "length": 29}}}});